                    "id": "17256676",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=balancap",
                        "name": "balancap",
                        "key": "balancap",
                        "avatarUrls": {
                            "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?ownerId=balancap&avatarId=45215",
                            "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=balancap&avatarId=45215",
                            "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&ownerId=balancap&avatarId=45215",
                            "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&ownerId=balancap&avatarId=45215"
                        },
                        "displayName": "Paul Balanca",
                        "active": true,
                        "timeZone": "Etc/UTC"
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks, I wanted to make sure any work I start would not conflict with the existing direction of the Arrow library project.\r\n\r\nI fully agree, we are in the realm of fine micro-optimizations. As we have experienced in FiveAI by increasingly using PyArrow as a backbone library for our internal tooling, data scientists / ML scientists enjoy being able to quickly experiment with some non-optimized dirty data pipeline, and we are trying to get as close as possible to Numpy performance in these cases. Which explains why this kind of library optimization can be useful, even if in a properly vectorized code it would not matter.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=balancap",
                        "name": "balancap",
                        "key": "balancap",
                        "avatarUrls": {
